{
  "texts": [
    "The Whigs had just abolished slavery and considered the drug trade to be a form of slavery.",
    "The conservatives also objected to the drug trade, though for different reasons.",
    "They viewed the drug trade as bad for business (in textiles and tea).",
    "The name of the conflict, Opium Wars, comes from an editorial on March 23, 1840, in the conservative newspaper: The Times, which argued that The British would be saddled with the massive expense of an unnecessary foreign campaign that would cost far more than the entire value of the lost opium.",
    "Platt (2019), p. 393."
  ]
}